    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7846681d_fea0dd29",
        "filename": "util/file/file_reader.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 188,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-27T16:37:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That would be an acceptable use for this, but that’s not how you’re using it.\n\nWeakStdioFileReader is a quirk that exists for really only one reason: to read input from stdin. It uses the FILE*-based stdio fread() library routine instead of the file descriptor-based raw read() system call because that’s normal for stdin. The “weak” nature of it is just because it’s pretty hazardous to outright close stdin, stdout, and stderr, at least without duping /dev/null over them.\n\nIn Crashpad, we generally limit stdio to just those three streams, and use the raw system call interface elsewhere. This becomes more important in code that may run in signal handler context, because stdio has internal locks and is not generally signal-safe. It’s not clear that this code will run in that context yet, but reducing the dangerous library surface area will help ensure that, especially where there’s a viable alternative available with no down-side.\n\nI don’t think that we should double down on WeakStdio by using it outside of the limited scopes where we basically need to.",
      "revId": "20e19b2def723d5c2a68e6f4aaf09a462947f2cc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9dca7983_8c3e2b2a",
        "filename": "util/file/file_reader.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 188,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-03-01T14:45:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e That would be an acceptable use for this, but that’s not how you’re using it.\n\u003e \n\u003e WeakStdioFileReader is a quirk that exists for really only one reason: to read input from stdin. It uses the FILE*-based stdio fread() library routine instead of the file descriptor-based raw read() system call because that’s normal for stdin. The “weak” nature of it is just because it’s pretty hazardous to outright close stdin, stdout, and stderr, at least without duping /dev/null over them.\n\u003e \n\u003e In Crashpad, we generally limit stdio to just those three streams, and use the raw system call interface elsewhere. This becomes more important in code that may run in signal handler context, because stdio has internal locks and is not generally signal-safe. It’s not clear that this code will run in that context yet, but reducing the dangerous library surface area will help ensure that, especially where there’s a viable alternative available with no down-side.\n\u003e \n\u003e I don’t think that we should double down on WeakStdio by using it outside of the limited scopes where we basically need to.\n\nI thought about this a little more and I think that I’m going to go a little bit easier. I think that we can allow some stdio here, at least for now.\n\nI don’t think that this new class is necessary. It just wraps getline(), let’s just use that. If you find that you really do need some sort of abstraction to wrap getline(), it shouldn’t be in this file. This file is for the FileReaderInterface-based stuff, which this is not. If it’s truly necessary, you can make the wrapper be local to the file that you need it in.",
      "parentUuid": "7846681d_fea0dd29",
      "revId": "20e19b2def723d5c2a68e6f4aaf09a462947f2cc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
