    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e64daa9c_3b97923b",
        "filename": "util/posix/process_info_linux.cc",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 139,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-27T16:37:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is going to be messed up if the clock is reset anytime after boot, because it’s based on the btime field from /proc/stat, which is probably the least reliable indication of time that we have anywhere. I don’t think we should trust btime for any purpose.\n\nWe should take the current value of CLOCK_BOOTTIME and subtract ticks_after_boot to tell us how many ticks ago the process started. Then we can convert that to a wall clock time by subtracting it from the current value of CLOCK_REALTIME.",
      "revId": "20e19b2def723d5c2a68e6f4aaf09a462947f2cc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "519c870b_57108dfa",
        "filename": "util/posix/process_info_linux.cc",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 144,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-02-27T16:37:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Definitely don’t open up the executable in this process. For one thing, it may have changed on disk. Crashpad handlers should never open up things that are mapped into a victim process’ address space. They should be able to access everything that they need by reading the victim’s state and accessing its memory.",
      "revId": "20e19b2def723d5c2a68e6f4aaf09a462947f2cc",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
